Data description¶

The business meaning of each column in the data is as below

  • GoodCredit: Whether the issued loan was a good decision or bad
  • checkingstatus: Status of existing checking account.
  • duration: Duration of loan in months
  • history: Credit history of the applicant
  • purpose: Purpose for the loan
  • amount: Credit amount
  • savings: Savings account/bonds
  • employ: Present employment since
  • installment: Installment rate in percentage of disposable income
  • status: Personal status and sex
  • others: Other debtors / guarantors for the applicant
  • residence: Present residence since
  • property: Property type of applicant
  • age: Age in years
  • otherplans: Other installment plans
  • housing: Housing
  • cards: Number of existing credits at this bank
  • job: Job
  • liable: Number of people being liable to provide maintenance for
  • tele: Is the Telephone registered or not
  • foreign: Is the applicant a foreign worker

Data Description¶

  • GoodCredit : This is the Target Variable. Categorical
  • checkingstatus1 : Categorical Variable
  • duration2 : Continuous Variable
  • history3 : Categorical Variable
  • purpose4 : Categorical Variable

def plotabarcharts(inpData, CatColslist):
    import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
    import math

    # Calculate the grid size
    n_cols = 3  # Number of columns in the subplot grid
    n_rows = math.ceil(len(CatColslist) / n_cols)  # Number of rows based on the number of columns

    # Create the subplots with increased size and spacing
    fig, subplots = plt.subplots(nrows=n_rows, ncols=n_cols, figsize=(15, 5 * n_rows))
    fig.tight_layout(pad=4.0)  # Adjust spacing between subplots

    for Colname, ax in zip(CatColslist, subplots.flatten()):  # Flatten the grid to easily iterate
        inpData.groupby(Colname).size().plot(kind='bar', ax=ax)
        

    plt.show()

# List of categorical columns
ColList = ['GoodCredit', 'checkingstatus', 'history', 'purpose', 'savings', 'employ', 'installment',

def plotboxchart(inpData, TarVar, Predcols):
    import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
    fig, subplots = plt.subplots(nrows = 1, ncols = len(Predcols),figsize = (18,6))

    for predictors, prednum in zip(Predcols, range(len(Predcols))):
        inpData.boxplot(column= predictors, by= TarVar, figsize = (6,6),vert=True ,ax= subplots[prednum])

In [224]:
def annovatest(inpData, TarVar, predCols):
    from scipy.stats import f_oneway

    selectedpreds = []

    for cols in predCols:
        GroupedData = inpData.groupby(TarVar)[cols].apply(list)
        AnnovaResults = f_oneway(*GroupedData)

        if AnnovaResults[1] < 0.05:
            print(f'{cols} is correlated with {TarVar} with p-Value - {AnnovaResults[1]}')
            selectedpreds.append(cols)

        else:
            print(f'{cols} is correlated NOT with {TarVar} with p-Value - {AnnovaResults[1]}')

    return selectedpreds

def plotgroupedBars(inpData, TarVar, Preds):
    import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
    import math

    ncols = 3
    nrows = math.ceil(len(Preds)/ncols)
    fig, subplots = plt.subplots(nrows= nrows, ncols=ncols, figsize=(nrows*6,80))
    subplots = subplots.flatten()

    
    for pred, i in zip(Preds, subplots):
        crosstabres = pd.crosstab(index= inpData[pred], columns=inpData[TarVar])
        crosstabres.plot.bar(color= ('red','green'), ax= i, title= pred + ' '+ 'Vs' +' '+ TarVar)

def functionchi2(inpData, TarVar, Preds):
    from scipy.stats import chi2_contingency

    SelectedPreds = []

    for predictor in Preds:
        Crosstab = pd.crosstab(index= inpData[predictor], columns=inpData[TarVar])
        chi2res = chi2_contingency(Crosstab)

        if chi2res[1] < 0.05:
            print(f'{predictor} is correlated with {TarVar} with p-Value - {chi2res[1]}')
            SelectedPreds.append(predictor)

        else:
            print(f'{predictor} is correlated NOT with {TarVar} with p-Value - {chi2res[1]}')
            
    return SelectedPreds

Treating Ordered Data¶

In [235]:
def sort_and_replace_with_numbers(df, columns):
    mapping_dict = {}  # Dictionary to store mappings for each column
    for column_name in columns:
        # Get the unique values from the column and sort them
        unique_values = sorted(df[column_name].unique())
        
        # Create a dictionary that maps each unique value to a number
        value_to_number = {value: i for i, value in enumerate(unique_values)}
        
        # Replace the values in the column with the corresponding numbers
        df[column_name].replace(value_to_number, inplace=True)
        
        # Store the mapping in the mapping_dict for reference
        mapping_dict[column_name] = value_to_number
    
    return df, mapping_dict  # Return the modified DataFrame and the mapping dictionary

# Example usage:
Replace_cols = ['checkingstatus', 'history', 'purpose', 'savings', 'employ', 'status', 'others', 
               'property', 'otherplans', 'housing', 'foreign']

DataForML, mappings = sort_and_replace_with_numbers(DataForML, Replace_cols)

# Display the mapping dictionary for all columns
print("Mapping of original values to numbers for all columns:", mappings)

# Display the modified DataFrame
print(DataForML.head())
